Yes—this is a bug in this early Tailwind version’s `@apply` implementation.

`borderStylesReset` intentionally makes the standalone style utilities non-rendering:

```css
.border-dotted { border-width: 0; }
```

The normal stylesheet then relies on utility order:

```css
.border-dotted { border-width: 0; }
.border { border: 1px solid …; }
.border-dotted { border-style: dotted; }
```

So `class="border border-dotted"` works. But `@apply` copies *both* matching `.border-dotted` rules into your component, including `border-width: 0`; therefore even `@apply border border-dotted` gets its width reset to zero.

The relevant behavior is in [substituteClassApplyAtRules.js](/testbed/src/lib/substituteClassApplyAtRules.js:30), which collects declarations from every matching selector.

A practical workaround in this revision is:

```css
.component {
  @apply border;
  border-style: dotted;
}
```

(or set an explicit non-zero `border-width` after applying `border-dotted`).

Also, `border-dotted` alone is not intended to create a visible border; it only selects the style. If it appears to work by itself, another rule is providing a non-zero border width.
